‚úÖ Step 1: Open Azure Cloud Shell
Go to https://shell.azure.com or open Cloud Shell from the Azure Portal (top navigation bar).

Choose Bash (not PowerShell).

Make sure your subscription and region are set correctly.

‚úÖ Step 2: Set Variables (Optional but recommended)

# Set your values
RESOURCE_GROUP="myResourceGroup"
LOCATION="eastus"
KEYVAULT_NAME="myKeyVault$RANDOM"
‚úÖ Step 3: Create Resource Group (If not already created)
az group create --name $RESOURCE_GROUP --location $LOCATION
‚úÖ Step 4: Create Azure Key Vault

az keyvault create --name $KEYVAULT_NAME --resource-group $RESOURCE_GROUP --location $LOCATION
‚úÖ Step 5: Add a Secret to Key Vault

az keyvault secret set --vault-name $KEYVAULT_NAME --name "MySecret" --value "ThisIsMySecretValue"
‚úÖ Step 6: List Secrets in Key Vault

az keyvault secret list --vault-name $KEYVAULT_NAME
‚úÖ Step 7: Get Secret Value

az keyvault secret show --vault-name $KEYVAULT_NAME --name "MySecret" --query value -o tsv
‚úÖ Step 8: Access from Azure VM (optional)
To access Key Vault from a VM, follow these:

Assign a Managed Identity to the VM.

Grant that identity access to Key Vault:

az keyvault set-policy --name $KEYVAULT_NAME --object-id <VM-IDENTITY-OBJECT-ID> --secret-permissions get list
Use the Azure Instance Metadata Service from the VM to retrieve secrets securely.

üìù Useful Tips:
Key Vault names must be globally unique.

You can store secrets, keys, and certificates in Key Vault.

Always use Managed Identities to access Key Vault from services like VM, App Service, or Function Apps.
